  "prompt": "Why do I feel sleepy and tired after consuming non-drowsy cold/flu-relief medication?",
  "response": "Feeling sleepy or tired after taking non-drowsy cold or flu medication can occur for several reasons:\n\n1. **Active Ingredients**: While marketed as \"non-drowsy,\" some medications can still have ingredients that may cause mild sedation in certain individuals. For example, some decongestants or antihistamines, even those labeled non-drowsy, might still affect your energy levels.\n\n2. **Illness**: The symptoms of a cold or flu itself can lead to fatigue. Your body is expending energy to fight off the virus, which can result in you feeling more tired than usual.\n\n3. **Dehydration**: Medications can sometimes lead to dehydration, which can contribute to feelings of tiredness. Ensuring adequate fluid intake can help mitigate this.\n\n4. **Individual Sensitivity**: People react differently to medications; what doesn't cause drowsiness in one person might affect another. Your body's unique chemistry can make you more sensitive to certain ingredients.\n\n5. **Other Medications or Supplements**: If you're taking other medications or supplements, there could be interactions that amplify sedative effects.\n\n6. **Placebo Effect**: Sometimes, the expectation of feeling tired after taking medication, even a non-drowsy one, can lead to experiencing such symptoms.\n\n7. **Sleep Disruption**: Cold and flu symptoms can disrupt your sleep quality, leading to tiredness. Even without drowsiness-inducing ingredients, if you're taking medication at night, it might indirectly affect your sleep patterns.\n\nIf you continue to feel excessively tired after taking medication, it's a good idea to consult with a healthcare professional to rule out any other potential causes or to adjust your medication.",
